<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-076-176  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 076 176.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Business  Feb 20 1989 v15 n4 p62(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The profits crisis in distribution: one way out. (executiveviewpoint)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gannaway, Peyton.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The electronics industry is experiencing a period of minimumprofit, forcing distributors to restructure with an emphasis onmaximizing profits.andP;  The average net profit margin for theindustry was below one percent between 1985 and 1987 with lessthan a three percent return on equity.andP;  The first half of 1988ended with only a 2.8 percent return on sales and less than 11percent return on equity.andP;  The reason for this downturn isattributed to the drive for increased sales in distribution.andP;  Itis suggested that an average net profit margin of five percent, anincrease of more than four percent, is needed for the industry tosustain itself.andP;  That goal can be achieved through higher grossmargins, lower cost of goods sold, lower interest expense andlower operating costs for the industry, which are all discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Distribution ManagementDistributorsProfit MarginElectronic IndustryIndustry Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   U.S. distributors' profits 1983-1988. (graph)U.S. distributors' costs 1983-1988. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>